    How to remove the forced newline that scanf comes with in C?

    This is a condensed code that I'm testing it with. It's basically a multiplication of two matrices containing only integers. As the user enters in the numbers for the matrices prompted by scanf, a newline is forced.

    For example, with a 2x2 matrix, as the user enters numbers, it displays like this:
    [ 1
    2
    ]
    [ 3
    4
    ]

    ...while I hoped it to be displayed like the way that displayMatrix() I wrote would do:
    [ 1 2 ]
    [ 3 4 ]

    I've look up on Google and tried all the methods that I found (ie. fgets chars and then convert to int, sscant, adding a getchar() right after scanf to remove \n from buffer, some others that I improvised, and etc), but so far none has worked...This is getting seriously frustrating, lmao!

    ps. I use gcc compiler on Ubuntu.

    ps2. I use plain pointer array to simulate 2D matrices because I'm cheap and weird. Don't judge. 8D

    #include<stdio.h>
    #include<stdlib.h>

    void displayMatrix(int *mat, int mm, int nn) {
    int counter = 0;

    for(int i = 0; i < mm; i++) {
    printf("[\t");
    for(int j = 0; j < nn; j++) {
    printf("%d\t", mat[counter]);
    counter++;
    }
    printf("]\n");
    }
    printf("\n");
    }

    void enterMatrix(int *mat, int mm, int nn) {
    int counter = 0;

    for(int i = 0; i < mm; i++) {
    printf("[\t");
    for(int j = 0; j < nn; j++) {
    scanf("%d", &mat[counter]);
    //printf("%d\t", mat[counter]);
    counter++;
    }
    printf("]\n");
    }
    printf("\n");
    }

    void matrixMulti(int *mat1, int *mat2, int m1, int n1, int m2, int n2) {
    int *temp = malloc(m1 * n2 * sizeof(int));
    int *temp2 = NULL;
    int counter = 0, sumTemp = 0;
    for(int i = 0; i < m1; i++) {
    for(int j = 0; j < n2; j++) {
    for(int k = 0; k < n1; k++)
    sumTemp = sumTemp + mat1[i+k] * mat2[j+k*n2];
    temp[counter] = sumTemp;
    counter++;
    }
    }
    temp2 = temp;
    for(int i = 0; i < m1 * n2; i++)
    mat1[i] = temp[i];
    free(temp);
    //displayMatrix(mat1, m1, n2);
    }

    int main(){
    int mm1 = 2, nn1 = 2, mm2 = 2, nn2 = 2;
    int *mat1 = malloc(mm1 * nn1 * sizeof(int));
    int *mat2 = malloc(mm2 * nn2 * sizeof(int));
    enterMatrix(mat1, mm1, nn1);
    enterMatrix(mat2, mm2, nn2);
    matrixMulti(mat1, mat2, mm1, nn1, mm2, nn2);
    displayMatrix(mat1, mm1, nn1);
    free(mat1);
    free(mat2);
    }

    Best Answer - Chosen by Asker

    You wont be able to fix this too easily

    the problem is
    reading from STDIN means that any INPUT has to WAIT for a completed
    RECORD. from STDIN a RECORD is a LINE terminated by NEW-LINE.

    so although you may say to scanf read one integer,
    scanf is effectively suspended until you type in a complete LINE into
    STDIN. In that line you could type 2,2,2,2, even though you might only
    want 2.

    Because any INPUT through STDIN gets immediately ECHOed to STDOUT
    you cant stop a CURSOR from getting incremented.

    there are things that can sometimes be done like CR and NL and CR-LF
    are all different
    Different operating systems use CR (Ctrl-d single character) to terminate a text line
    of input. These tend to be older operating systems.
    newer operating systems use New Line which is line feed carriage return.
    so in transferring text files between oerating systems
    you sometimes have to add a line feed or in some cases a carriage return
    to make the text files right for the destination operating system.

    these stem as far back as the 70's when all we had were Teletypes and to speed
    things up when you pressed Carriage Return an additional Line Feed was
    issued to save you time not having to press another key.
    but editors just stored the carriage return not the line feed

    in other words STDIN works like a teletype.

    inevitably this means that users end up scanning for characters themselves
    because the input is echoed outside of the control of the C.

    There are equivalent bios calls to do a string in with echo and without echo
    so you can fiddle with BIOS calls instead but this is only useful in dos mode
    applications.

    what usually happens is
    you create a buffer(string) for a LINE
    you fill it with text that you want to display
    you uses SSCANF instead and make it fill the buffer, taking care to prefiill
    section of the buffer with spaces, making sure you fill at specific positions
    sort of like a cursor.
    once the buffer is ready, then you can
    issue an Up-arrow(line up) + option carriage return(without line feed) depending on
    specific cursor controls
    and rewrite the string
    you can then selectively choose when to LINE FEED yourself

    this will lead to blinks and flashes but because you build a line
    yourself and fill at least some stuff on the left then your eyes
    wont notice it too badly

    you may get better results to learn cursor psoitioning too
    so the input always happens say on line 5 (for example) rather than
    always at the bottom line that keeps scrolling
